SIMPLE: revive
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Revive
<hw>Re*vive"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p.
p.</pos> <conjf>Revived</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Reviving</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[F. <ets>revivere</ets>, L.
<ets>revivere</ets>; pref. <ets>re-</ets> re- + <ets>vivere</ets> to
live. See <er>Vivid</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To return to life; to
recover life or strength; to live anew; to become reanimated or
reinvigorated.</def> <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The Lord heard the voice of Elijah; and the soul of the child came
into again, and he <qex>revived</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>1 Kings xvii.
22.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Hence, to recover from a state of oblivion,
obscurity, neglect, or depression; <as>as, classical learning
<ex>revived</ex> in the fifteenth century</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Old Chem.)</fld> <def>To recover its natural or
metallic state, as a metal.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Revive</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Revive
<hw>Re*vive"</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <ety>[Cf. F. <ets>reviver</ets>. See
<er>Revive</er>, <pos>v. i.</pos>]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To restore, or
bring again to life; to reanimate.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Those bodies, by reason of whose mortality we died, shall be
<qex>revived</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Bp. Pearson.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To raise from coma, languor, depression, or
discouragement; to bring into action after a suspension.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Those gracious words <qex>revive</qex> my drooping thoughts.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Your coming, friends, <qex>revives</qex> me.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Hence, to recover from a state of neglect or disuse;
<as>as, to <ex>revive</ex> letters or learning</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To renew in the mind or memory; to bring to
recollection; to recall attention to; to reawaken.</def>
⟦ldquo⟧<xex>Revive</xex> the libels born to die.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Swift.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The mind has a power in many cases to <qex>revive</qex>
perceptions which it has once had.</q> <rj><qau>Locke.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <fld>(Old Chem.)</fld> <def>To restore or reduce to its
natural or metallic state; <as>as, to <ex>revive</ex> a metal after
calcination</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Revivement</ent>⟦br⟧
